CHIKUNGUNYA - INDIAN OCEAN UPDATE (02): REUNION
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Fri, 24 Feb 2006 05:07:38 -0500 (EST)
From: A-Lan Banks <a-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Reuters AlertNet, 24 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L23786228.htm>

A mosquito-borne disease has directly or indirectly killed 77 people
on France's Indian Ocean island of La Reunion, French Health Minister
Xavier Bertrand said on Thursday.
Chikungunya fever, for which there is no known cure or vaccine, had
affected some 130 000 people [an incidence rate of 16.8 per cent] on
the island off the southeast coast of Africa. Bertrand said that was
20 000 more than a week ago.
Around one in 6 inhabitants has now been affected on Reunion, which
has a total population of some 775 000 people.
"The last numbers ... refer to 77 deaths, directly or indirectly
attributable to the epidemic for the month of January 2006," Bertrand
said. "(This is) a radically new situation, which was not expected
because scientific research showed that chikungunya did not kill," he
said.
The illness, which has also travelled to the nearby Indian Ocean islands of
the Seychelles and Mauritius [and Mayotte. - Mod.JW], is marked by high fever
and severe [joint pains and]rashes. Most people recover although it is
extremely painful.
First recognized in East Africa in 1952, it also leaves the immune
system weak, [providing] opportunities for other diseases to set in.
The name chikungunya comes from the Swahili for stooped walk,
referring to the posture of those afflicted.
French Prime Minister Dominique de Villepin, who is to travel to
Reunion on Sunday, said the entire island should be ridden of
mosquitoes to stop the disease from spreading.
Villepin said it was still safe to visit the island, which is a
popular tourist destination for European travellers. The Reunion
Committee on Tourism has reported tour cancellations but has not
provided figures for costs incurred.
"You can certainly go there. The proof is that I'm going there,"
Villepin told Canal Plus television. "You have to take some
precautions and use (certain) products," he said.
Authorities say people should remove stagnant water, use mosquito
repellents and bed nets and spray bedrooms at night.
