[2]
Date: Fri, 24 Feb 2006 05:07:38 -0500 (EST)
From: A-Lan Banks <a-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: New Scientist, 24 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.newscientist.com/article.ns?id=dn8765>

A team of 4 experts from the World Health Organization has left for
the Indian Ocean island of Reunion to investigate a massive outbreak
of a debilitating mosquito-borne disease which causes its victims to
double over.
The largest-ever epidemic of the chikungunya virus among people in
Reunion started in February 2005, but has gathered pace since
December 2005, spreading to neighbouring countries.
Reports and estimates suggest that 110 000 of the island's 800 000 population
has been afflicted by the stooping disease, says WHO, although official
figures, from a voluntary sentinel system on the island, suggest just 1700
cases. During the first week of February 2006, Mauritius reported 206 cases
and the Seychelles reported 1255 cases. [110 000 is an estimate, based on
extrapolating the number detected by the sentinel physicians to the entire
population. - Mod.JW]
The WHO experts will assess the current actions being taken to fight
the chikungunya virus's spread, which include educating people about
how to protect themselves against the disease and bolstering
epidemiological surveillance.
People infected by the virus can also experience recurring episodes
of pain, even after the virus appears to have cleared from their
bodies, says Robert Tesh, an expert on mosquito-borne viruses at the
University of Texas Medical Branch in Galveston, USA. He says that
these returning arthritic pains may be caused by an immune system
response.
Tesh explains that no quick treatment exists for chikungunya disease. Doctors
primarily help to alleviate the symptoms, such as fever and
dehydration. "There isn't much else you can do," he says, adding that
he knows of no approved vaccine against the virus.
Chikungunya is typically found in sub-Saharan Africa and tropical regions of
Asia as far away as Indonesia. As for why such a large outbreak would occur in
the southwest Indian Ocean, Tesh says that this may have something to do
with "herd immunity". This describes the phenomenon in which populations
infected by the virus recover and gain immunity against it. When there are
enough people in one location who boast immunity to chikungunya, the virus
cannot easily pass from one host to another and cause an outbreak. Conversely,
if there has been no outbreak for a long time, herd immunity falls as fewer
people have encountered the disease before, allowing the virus to spread more
effectively.
"Weather can also play a role as it affects the abundance and
activity of the mosquitoes that transmit the virus," Tesh adds. Wet
conditions, for example, can cause an upsurge in mosquito populations.
[Byline: Roxanne Khamsi]
